The Telegraph - Calcutta
 Saturday, November 30, 2002 				Metro Recommends
				 																The Book				 																																	(Alka Saraogi)				 																																	lIt is the story of Calcutta in the last century, from pre to post-Independence, told through the eyes of the main protagonist, Kishore Babu. He narrates his experiences as he travels through time, journeying through the city on foot, from his great-grandfathers story to his own present				 																The Event				 																																	(Salt Lake Stadium, December 1, 5 pm)				 																																	lIts toon time for the kids, with the main characters from Cartoon Network, including Tom and Jerry, Dee Dee and Dexter and the Powerpuff Girls dropping in for a chat and a game or two. Music, dance, contests and prizes are on the cards for the young fans. The show is being presented in association with Telekids.				 																The Show				 																																	(GD Birla Sabhagar, December 5, 6.30 pm)				 																																	lA traditional Japanese instrumental concert, comprising three-string guitar and drums, by four visiting performers. Organised by the Consulate-General and the Japan Foundation in honour of the 50th anniversary of Indo-Japan diplomatic relations				 																The CD				 																																	(George Benson)				 																																	lThis masterpiece by the guitar great is now available on CD. Phil Upchurchs rhythm and bass blend perfectly with Bensons felicity on the fretboard. Watch out for Ronnie Fosters electric piano solo in So This Is Love?
